The University of California, Santa Cruz offers many visual performing arts opportunities. The most popular ones being Baile Folkloric and Theater. Everyone is welcome to participate in these organizations.

[Isabella Quinn-Rodriguez, Los Mejicas, UCSC, 28 May 2025](https://www.instagram.com/p/DKNsXKvBuQP/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&igsh=MzRlODBiNWFlZA==) 

The Baile Folklorico organization, more commonly known as Los Mejicas, is one of the most enduring student organizations on campus. Founded in 1972, it is the longest running club at UCSC and the very first Baile Folklorico group in the entire UC system. According to [Seguimos zapateando \- News](https://news.ucsc.edu/2022/10/los-mejicas-anniversary/), for over 50 years, Los Mejicas has welcomed students to explore the traditions of  Mexican folklore dance, offering a creative outlet by performing and cultural education.   

Baile Folklorico is more than just dancing; it is a way to express the historical culture of Mexico. Each region of Mexico has its own unique style, costume, and rhythm, reflecting on the stories and traditions of the community. For many, students join to have a connection with their heritage. Los Mejicas preserve these traditions by sharing them with the audiences across campus.   

As a registered student organization, Los Mejicas receive support from SOMeCA (Student Organization Advising & Resources, Student Media, and Culture & Arts Division). According to [Connect with Student Organizations](https://getinvolved.ucsc.edu/student-organizations/), SOMeCA provides them with advising, event planning, and budget guidance, along with access to rehearsal spaces, performance venues, and promotional support. These resources are crucial for the group, yet there are still financial needs. Costumes, for example, are different for every region and are often required to be kept maintained.    

To help with these costs, Los Mejicas participated in the annual fundraising event known as Giving Day. During this event, student organizations compete in exciting challenges that encourage donations from people. According to [UC Santa Cruz | 50 years of Mejicas\!](https://ucsc.scalefunder.com/cfund/project/32883), Giving Day provides funds for travel and wardrobe expenses, allowing the group to continue performing.   

However, despite their long history and cultural importance, Los Mejicas still struggle financially. The club relies heavily on student contributions and donations, which can be insufficient at times. This situation can feel unequal when compared to other UC campuses, where their folklorico groups often receive direct funding from their university. Those clubs enjoy greater resources and more opportunities to perform. Despite these challenges, Los Mejicas focuses on sustaining its legacy.   

At the same time, the group faces a unique problem about their identity. Los Mejicas has chosen to remain a student organization rather than transition into a formal campus club. Their priority is cultural learning through traditional dancing, not treating it as a hobby. Becoming a club would mean losing the support of SOMeCA, which as we know provides them with multiple resources. While school funding could ease finances, it would end their connections with SOMeCA. There is no perfect solution, they would have to choose between accepting funds and risk erasing their legacy, while staying independent preserves cultural integrity but limits financial support. For the members, keeping traditions outweighs fundings.   

Another issue is how folklorico is categorized within the university system. While dance requires athleticism, teamwork, and dedication, it does not necessarily fit into the category of sports. As a result, Los Mejicas does not receive the same funding that athletic clubs enjoy. The distinction feels unfair, as folklorico is just as much physical effort and discipline as a typical sport.   

Regardless of these obstacles, Los Mejicas continue to thrive because of the passionate members. Their performances are not only a showcase but a cultural celebration that enriches the community at UCSC. Looking forward the club hopes for greater recognition and consistent funding, which would ultimately allow Los Mejicas to expand.   

Ultimately, Los Mejicas is more than just a dance club. It is a community of dedicated students and a symbol of pride. It has carried forward a legacy of Baile Folklorico on campus, providing resilience and commitment.
